{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583087"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:06:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1982"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1982"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110396"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1982"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1982"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92670"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110396"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDobutamine is a synthetic catecholamine used clinically as an inotropic agent. While its primary effect is to increase cardiac contractility, it also causes peripheral vasodilation through a specific receptor-mediated mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following adrenergic receptors mediates the vasodilatory effect of dobutamine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-1 adrenergic receptor","Alpha-2 adrenergic receptor","Beta-1 adrenergic receptor","Beta-2 adrenergic receptor","Dopamine D1 receptor"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDobutamine causes vasodilation primarily through its agonist activity at \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E located on vascular smooth muscle cells. When activated, these receptors couple to Gs proteins, leading to increased adenylyl cyclase activity and cyclic AMP production. This activates protein kinase A, which phosphorylates various proteins involved in smooth muscle contraction, ultimately resulting in vasodilation and decreased peripheral vascular resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E mediate vasoconstriction when activated, not vasodilation. Dobutamine has minimal activity at these receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-2 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily located presynaptically where they inhibit noradrenaline release. While their activation can indirectly lead to vasodilation, dobutamine does not significantly interact with these receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-1 adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary target of dobutamine and are responsible for its positive inotropic and chronotropic effects on the heart. However, these receptors are not significantly expressed in vascular smooth muscle and do not mediate vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine D1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vasodilation in certain vascular beds (particularly renal and mesenteric), but dobutamine does not have significant activity at dopamine receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe beta-2 receptor-mediated vasodilation can sometimes offset the increased cardiac output from beta-1 stimulation, potentially leading to hypotension in some patients receiving dobutamine therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Cthead\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EReceptor\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPrimary Location\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EEffect on Vasculature\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EDobutamine Activity\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/thead\u003E\u003Ctbody\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAlpha-1\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EVascular smooth muscle\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EVasoconstriction\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EMinimal\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAlpha-2\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EPresynaptic terminals\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EIndirect vasodilation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENone\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EBeta-1\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EHeart\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENo direct effect\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EStrong agonist\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EBeta-2\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EVascular smooth muscle\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EVasodilation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EModerate agonist\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EDopamine D1\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERenal/mesenteric vessels\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EVasodilation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENone\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/tbody\u003E\u003C/table\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dobutamine is a synthetic catecholamine that acts primarily on beta-1 adrenergic receptors to increase cardiac contractility.","The vasodilation caused by dobutamine results from its agonist activity at beta-2 adrenergic receptors in vascular smooth muscle.","Beta-2 receptor activation leads to smooth muscle relaxation through increased cyclic AMP production and activation of protein kinase A."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook, 2020. \u2018Comparative information for sympathomimetics\u2019, accessed 11/4/20"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92670"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1982"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92670","li